&lt;h2 id="simulation-and-results">Simulation and Results&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>The calibration of the PIHM model used the Covariance Matrix Adaptation Evolution Strategy (CMA-ES) (Hansen 2006,Auger 2005). The automatic CMA-ES calibration is robust and able to converge to global optimization with low computing cost.&lt;/p>
&lt;h3 id="river-discharge">River discharge&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>The stream flow in the watershed follows the seasonal variation of precipitation. During drought years, the base flow from groundwater depletion contributes to the streamflow, and the excess infiltration replenishes ground water in wet seasons. For small watersheds in the Central Valley, such as catchment #9 where precipitation is less and the aquifer is thicker, the contribution from groundwater is small.&lt;/p>
&lt;figure class="image">
&lt;img src="fig/calib.png">
&lt;figcaption>Calibration based on discharge of four subcatchments&lt;/figcaption>
&lt;/figure>
&lt;h3 id="ground-water-variation">Ground water variation&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>The ground water near the river channel is shallower than the hill-slope. The spatial distribution pattern of ground water is controlled by topography, soil/geology characteristics and shape of the watershed. Steep slopes store less ground water than moderate slopes, because a steep hydraulic gradient on steep slopes drive the lateral groundwater flow.&lt;/p>
